  {q:"What is the best free stock screener?",a:"The best free stock screeners include Finviz, Yahoo Finance, TradingView, and our tool here. Finviz offers the most filters (70+), TradingView has the best charting integration, and Yahoo Finance is the most beginner-friendly. Our screener focuses on S&P 500 large caps with instant filtering by market cap, PE ratio, dividend yield, sector, and 52-week performance — no account required."},
  {q:"What PE ratio is considered good for stocks?",a:"A PE ratio under 15 is generally considered 'value' territory, 15–25 is the market average range, and above 25 suggests growth pricing. However, PE varies dramatically by sector — tech stocks average PE 30+ while utilities average 15–18. A 'good' PE depends on growth rate: a PE of 30 is reasonable for a company growing earnings 25% annually (PEG ratio of 1.2) but expensive for one growing at 5%."},
  {q:"How do I screen for value stocks?",a:"Screen for value stocks using: PE ratio under 20 (ideally under 15), dividend yield above 2%, and a price below intrinsic value. Use our 'Value Stocks' preset which filters for PE under 20 and dividend yield above 2%. Classic value metrics also include price-to-book under 3 and PEG ratio under 1. Warren Buffett adds qualitative filters: strong moat, consistent earnings, and competent management."},
  {q:"What is market cap and why does it matter for screening?",a:"Market capitalization is a company's total stock market value (share price × shares outstanding). Large cap ($10B+) stocks are more stable with lower growth, mid caps ($2–10B) balance growth and stability, and small caps (under $2B) offer higher growth potential with more volatility. Market cap matters because it determines risk profile — conservative investors screen for large caps ($50B+) while aggressive growth investors look at smaller companies."},
  {q:"How do I find dividend stocks with a screener?",a:"To find quality dividend stocks, screen for: dividend yield above 2% (but below 8% to avoid yield traps), 25+ consecutive years of dividend increases for Dividend Aristocrats, payout ratio below 75% (ensuring sustainability), and positive earnings growth. Our 'Dividend Champions' preset identifies S&P 500 companies with 25+ years of consecutive dividend increases — the most reliable dividend payers."},
  {q:"What is 52-week performance and how should I use it in screening?",a:"52-week performance shows a stock's price change over the past year as a percentage. Momentum investors screen for stocks up 20%+ (relative strength), while value investors look for beaten-down stocks (negative 52-week change) that may be undervalued. Be cautious with extreme readings: stocks down 40%+ may have fundamental problems, not just temporary dips."},
  {q:"How often should I run a stock screener?",a:"For long-term investors, monthly or quarterly is sufficient — PE ratios and dividend yields don't change dramatically day-to-day. Swing traders may screen weekly. Avoid the temptation to screen daily and overtrade. The best approach: set your criteria, identify candidates, then do deep research on the top 5–10 results before making investment decisions."}
